# Patterns and conventions

## File and naming conventions

- API routes: app/server/api/**/name.method.ts where method ∈ {get, post, patch, delete}. Directory structure mirrors URL path
- Services: app/server/services/* encapsulate business logic. Prefer thin API handlers that delegate to services
- Clients: DB/Redis/queues/email integrations under app/server/clients/*
- Validation: Use Zod (app/schema/zod.ts) for request/response shapes when applicable
- Auth: Use server/middleware/auth.ts; for admin APIs add requireAdmin.ts at handler start
- Errors: Wrap handlers with withErrorHandler.ts or use handleApiError.ts inside try/catch blocks
- Tests: Co-locate unit/integration tests under __tests__ in each domain (lib, server/api, server/services). E2E tests under app/tests/e2e
- Forecast modules: services/forecast/* are small, focused classes with clear inputs/outputs; avoid cross-module state coupling; prefer explicit arguments and typed returns
- DB schema:
  - Monetary fields use Decimal(19,2) unless noted (e.g., display_balance Decimal(36,18) for tokens)
  - Fields marked with /// @encrypted are handled by prisma-field-encryption; do not manually decrypt in app code
  - Keep schema comments and map names in sync with migrations

## Safe code changes

- Adding an API endpoint
  - Create file under app/server/api/<feature>/<name>.<method>.ts
  - Enforce auth/access early; consider account membership helpers (server/lib/accountAccess.ts, accountMembership.ts)
  - Validate inputs using Zod schemas
  - Delegate to a service; add unit tests in app/server/api/__tests__/ covering success/failure
- Changing DB schema
  - Edit app/prisma/schema.prisma
  - Generate and apply migration: pnpm --filter dineros-app exec prisma migrate dev (local) -> commit SQL under app/prisma/migrations
  - Regenerate client: pnpm --filter dineros-app exec prisma generate
  - If microservice relies on affected models, mirror changes in microservice/prisma/schema.prisma and run its prisma generate
  - Update seeds/tests affected by schema changes
- Field encryption
  - Mark sensitive fields with /// @encrypted (and optional hash annotations)
  - After schema changes, run prisma generate to update reencrypt/*
  - For key rotation or post-restore workflows, prefer generated reencrypt migrators; see docs/post-restore-encryption-plan.md
- Queues/cron
  - New background jobs go to server/queues/* with a corresponding service; expose admin toggles only if needed
  - Use nuxt-cron for scheduled tasks under server/cron/*
- Rate limiting
  - Use server/lib/rateLimitRedis.ts for request-scoped rate limiting

## PR and CI expectations

- Lint and tests must pass (see .github/workflows/pr.yml). Pre-commit runs TruffleHog and secret hygiene checks
- Do not commit .env files (blocked via pre-commit hook). Use .env.example for placeholders
- For schema governance: npm script prisma:check-governance (scripts/check-prisma-schema-governance.mjs)
- E2E snapshots vs staging are managed in a separate workflow; do not update via CI unless running the staging snapshot workflow

## Common pitfalls

- DATABASE_URL is required for prisma generate at build; Dockerfiles set a placeholder. When running locally in cloud agents, override injected production/staging DATABASE_URL per AGENTS.md
- Some tests mock integrations; ensure TZ=UTC env so date logic is stable
- If you change encrypted fields, expect migrations and possibly the post-restore script to need updates
